Short answer: ❌ No — jti is not only for refresh tokens.

But…

✅ In practice, it is most commonly used for refresh tokens.

Let’s clarify properly.

🧠 What jti Actually Is

In JSON Web Token, jti (JWT ID) is:

A unique identifier for a specific token instance.

It can be added to any JWT:

Access token

Refresh token

Email verification token

Password reset token

It’s just a unique ID.

🔥 When Is jti Used in Access Tokens?
🟢 Case 1 — Fully Stateless System

If your access tokens are:

Very short-lived (5–15 minutes)

Not stored in DB

Not individually revoked

Then you usually don’t need jti.

Why?

Because:

You don’t track access tokens.

You just verify signature + expiry.

Once expired → done.

Many simple microservices do this.

🟢 Case 2 — You Want Access Token Revocation

If you want to:

Immediately revoke access tokens

Blacklist compromised tokens

Detect replay attacks

Then you must add jti.

Because you need a way to identify that specific token.

Example:

{
  "sub": "42",
  "exp": 1700000000,
  "jti": "abc-123"
}

Then store:

jti = abc-123
revoked = false

Now you can revoke just that token.

🔥 Why jti Is More Important for Refresh Tokens

Refresh tokens:

Live longer (days/weeks)

Are more powerful

Must support rotation

Must detect reuse

So almost always:

✅ Refresh tokens have jti
✅ Stored in DB
✅ Marked revoked when rotated

Without jti, rotation is impossible.

🎯 Real-World Pattern

Most production systems do:

Access Token

Short-lived

Stateless

No DB check

May or may not include jti

Refresh Token

Long-lived

Stored in DB

Always has jti

Supports rotation

So in practice:

jti is critical for refresh tokens
Optional for access tokens

🏗 Simple Rule

If you need to track the token → use jti.
If you don’t track it → not required.

🏁 Final Answer

Is jti used only for refresh token?

❌ No — it can be used in any JWT.
✅ But it is most important and commonly used in refresh tokens.

